<h3 class="heading"><span class="type">Paragraph</span></h3>
<p>In Differential Calculus you saw that while it is <em class="emphasis">not</em> generally true that</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="./knowl/eq-NewbyError2.html">
\begin{equation}
\dfdx{(y\cdot z)}{x}=  \dfdx{y}{x}\cdot\dfdx{z}{x}\tag{1.3}
\end{equation}
</div>
<p class="continuation">there are certain pairs of functions which are exceptions; for which <a href="" class="xref" data-knowl="./knowl/eq-NewbyError2.html" title="Equation 1.3">equation (1.3)</a> is true. Let’s explore this problem in more detail.  We will switch to prime notation for aesthetic reasons.</p>
<span class="incontext"><a href="section-4.html#p-83" class="internal">in-context</a></span>
</body>
